"Political forces," he adds, "must converge on the underlying issues starting from Western membership and the distinction between allies, with which we can disagree but share the basic values, and the simple partners." "The idea of the book is to offer a reading of the dynamics of international relations by offering a tool to look at the world as it is and not as we would like it to be," Massolo, former secretary general of the Farnesina> and director of the Department of Security Information (Dis). "Today there is no single country that can define on its own all the themes of the global agenda," he explains, "we live in an anarchist world with multiple threats in which challenges and conflicts are all potentially existential, think of a war between the US and China, between the United States and Russia or between Israel and Iran, as well as would leave Europe without defense or do nothing against climate change or to rule artificial intelligence."
<div </div
&nbsp;
The good news, Massolo observes, is that "in fact each conflict bears in itself mitigating factors resulting from the fact that there are forces that draw in opposite directions". The individual countries must, however, equip themselves for this new scenario, "reflecting themselves as States, thinking of defence, making their economic systems resilient."
For the president of Mundys the two great international crises, Ukraine and the Middle East, have different dynamics.> "In Ukraine it tends to the stall," he says, "no one of the two parts is able to prevail entirely on the other, and then in the end it will come to an order that can be negotiated from Kiev with Moscow or a simple freezing of the state of fact, to Korean."
"To help Ukraine does not help them win the war but to secure four-fifths of its territory," says Massolo, "Europe cannot afford that from here to 3-4 years Putin begins his policy of aggression: For this reason it must avoid that the next president of the United States, whatever it is, accepts a 'quick-fix' for Ukraine at the expense of Europeans, and at the time often prepare to go anyway to end the war the prospect is of a counterposition, and not of a collaboration, with Moscow".
In this sense a summary will also be found on the authorization to Kiev to use European weapons to hit installations in Russia > from which attacks start: "From the point of view of coherence the defence of Ukraine passes from there," says Massolo. On the dynamics of the conflict in the Gaza Strip and its regional repercussions, however, the former president of the Ispi sees the conditions for "the evolution towards a new Middle East order with the extension of the Abraham's Agreements" between Israel and the moderate Sunni Arab countries.
There are in fact "the convergent interests of Israel to a security guaranteed by the U.S. > and supported by the Arab front, of the Sunni Arab countries, first of all Saudi Arabia, for the weapons of Israel and the U.S. defense, and that of the Palestinians for the recognition and perspective of the two States that only the U.S. can guarantee". "The same Iran, if the Ayatollah-Pasdaran balances do not change, has an interest in revoking sanctions and cannot neglect the relationship with its public opinion and an opposition that is not organized but represents much of the country," says Massolo. The real unknown concerns Prime Minister Netanyahu> who "has a personal agenda incompatible with the end of the conflict". &nbsp;
