AGI - It was a night of intense bombing on Rafah and clashes in the city of the extreme south of Gaza, after Israel declared that it had taken control of the Philadelphi corridor, a strategic bearing along the border between the Palestinian territory and Egypt. The military spokesman, Admiral Daniel Hagari, announced that Israel took the "operational control" of the narrow border area, where he said that "about 20 tunnels were discovered". Egypt, a long-standing mediator in the conflict and increasingly explicit critic of the Israeli operation, rejected the allegations that the tunnels were used to smuggle weapons. "Israel using these accusations to justify the continuation of the operation on Rafah," said a high-level Egyptian source at the daily Al-Qahera News. Egyptian officials said that a potential Israeli acquisition of the Philadelphi corridor would be a violation of the historic peace agreement between the two countries of 1979. During a visit to Beijing, Egyptian President Abdel Fattah al-Sisi called for greater humanitarian assistance for Gaza and reiterated the long-standing opposition of his country to "any attempt to force the Palestinians to flee from their land."
&nbsp;
Chinese leader Xi Jinping, for his part, called for a "wide, authoritative and effective international peace conference". On the field, witnesses reported fighting in the central and western part of Rafah and that Israeli forces demolished several buildings in the eastern parts of the city. The artillery hits reached the Zeitun district, in Gaza City, in the north of the territory, where thick smoking plums rose from the refugee camps of Jabalia and Beit Lahia. A constant flow of civilians is on the run from Rafah, carrying their possessions on their shoulders, by car or on wagons driven by donkeys.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The bombing last weekend, which killed 45 people in a refugee camp, aroused a wave of new convictions, including a social media campaign with the slogan "All eyes on Rafah" which was shared by tens of millions of users. The next day of the attack, Algeria presented a UN resolution project "by closing an immediate ceasefire and respected by all parties" and the release of all hostages, but it is not clear when it will be put to vote. Yesterday, in a phone call with Abu Mazen, Emmanuel Macron said that Paris was "determined to work with Algeria" to ensure that the council "makes a strong statement on Rafah" and invited the Palestinian president to "act the necessary reforms", offering the "prospective of the recognition of the State of Palestine".
&nbsp;
Israeli national security advisor Tzachi Hanegbi said that the war could continue until the end of the year and US Secretary of State Antony Blinken invited Israel to quickly develop a postwar strategy for Gaza, underlining: "In the absence of a plan for the next day, there will not be a day later." The New York Times and CNN, citing weapons experts and video analysis of the Rafah attack scene, reported that the bomb that is believed to have triggered the fire that tens of people were an American manufacturing GBU-39.

